[[Image:Bradford1911.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The club's 1911 FA Cup winning side&mdash;the only major honour to be won by Bradford City]]
This is a list of '''Bradford City A.F.C. seasons''' in English and European [[football (soccer)|football]], from 1903&mdash;when the club was formed&mdash;to the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season. It details the club's achievements in senior league and cup competitions, European competitions and the top scorers for each season. The list of top scorers also chronicles how the club's scoring records have progressed throughout the club's history.

[[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] were formed in 1903 and was elected into [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] before it had even played a game. Bradford City and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], in 1905, remain the only teams to be elected into the league before playing a competitive fixture.<ref>{{cite book
| last = Frost
| first = Terry
| title = Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988
| publisher = Breedon Books Sport
| year = 1988
| pages = p13
| isbn = 0907969380}}</ref> The club was promoted to [[Football League First Division|Division One]] when it won the Division Two title in [[1907-08 in English football|1907&ndash;08]]. In [[1910-11 in English football|1910&ndash;11]] the club recorded its highest league position of fifth and also won its only major honour when captain [[Jimmy Speirs]] lifted the [[FA Cup]] after he scored the only goal to defeat [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 1&ndash;0 in the [[FA Cup Final 1911|final]] replay.<ref>Telegraph & Argus ([[13 August]] [[2007]]), [http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1612976.0.leader_on_the_pitch_and_the_battlefield.php Leader on the pitch and the battlefield]</ref> Bradford City's honours also include the [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three (North)]] title in [[1928-29 in English football|1928&ndash;29]] and [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] crown in [[1984-85 in English football|1984&ndash;85]], as well as the [[Football League Third Division North Cup|Third Division North Challenge Cup]] in [[1938-39 in English football|1938&ndash;39]].

The club has spent two seasons in the [[Premier League]]. In [[1999-2000 in English football|1999&ndash;2000]], it avoided relegation with just 36 points, then a record low to stay up, after defeating [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] 1&ndash;0 in the final game with a headed goal from [[David Wetherall]].<ref>BBC Sport ([[29 June]] [[2000]]), [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/803023.stm Bradford pull off great escape]</ref> The club has won promotion in a total of eight seasons and been relegated on ten occasions; three relegations in the previous seven seasons meant the [[2007-08 in English football|2007&ndash;08]] season would be its first in the [[Football League Two|fourth tier]] in 26 years. ''The Bantams'' have also played in European competition when they took one of England's two places in the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup|Intertoto Cup]] in [[UEFA Intertoto Cup 2000|2000]]. Bradford defeated [[FK Atlantas]] and [[RKC Waalwijk]] before being knocked out by [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg]] in the semi-finals.<ref>BBC Sport ([[2 August]] [[2000]]), [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/863882.stm Bantams Euro dream over]</ref>

